structured_data.name: Güterverkehr (Freight Transport)
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface - Destatis thematic portal navigation
structured_data.description: Destatis (German Federal Statistical Office) thematic portal section on freight transport (Güterverkehr) under the Transport and Traffic (Transport und Verkehr) category. This section provides statistical data on goods transport activities in Germany. The portal serves as a gateway to various transport and traffic-related statistics maintained by Destatis.

structured_data.name: Fahrzeugbestand (Vehicle Fleet Statistics)
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query - data accessible through KBA (Kraftfahrt-Bundesamt) website with annual counts and interim quarterly updates
structured_data.data_format: Web-based database query interface with tabular data presentation
structured_data.description: Annual vehicle fleet inventory maintained by the German Federal Motor Transport Authority (KBA) covering all motor vehicles (Kfz) and vehicle trailers registered in the Central Vehicle Register (ZFZR) as of January 1st each year. Data includes vehicle classifications, manufacturers, fuel types, emission standards (Euro classes), holder demographics, and vehicle age statistics. Since 2018, interim counts are also available on April 1st, July 1st, and October 1st. As of January 1, 2024, the dataset covers 69.1 million vehicles total with 49.1 million passenger cars. Update frequency: Annual with quarterly interim updates.
structured_data.granularity: National (Germany) with regional breakdown by federal state (Bundesland), registration district (Zulassungsbezirk), and municipality (Gemeinde)

structured_data.name: Emissionen des Verkehrs
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with downloadable files (PDF diagrams and Excel data files)
structured_data.description: Dataset from Umweltbundesamt (German Federal Environment Agency) covering greenhouse gas emissions and air pollutants from the transportation sector in Germany. Includes data on CO2 emissions from passenger cars (Pkw) and heavy-duty vehicles (Lkw), nitrogen oxide (NOx) emissions, and particulate matter (PM10) emissions. Data spans from 1990 to 2023, with emphasis on trends since 1995. The dataset tracks the transportation sector's contribution to total German greenhouse gas emissions (21.7% in 2023) and its role in air pollution. Updated as of May 13, 2025.

structured_data.name: Treibhausgas-Emissionen in Deutschland
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with embedded tables and downloadable PDF files
subsector: Commercial and Institutional Buildings and Facilities
structured_data.description: Comprehensive greenhouse gas emissions inventory for Germany covering direct and indirect emissions from 1990 to 2024. Published by Umweltbundesamt (German Federal Environment Agency). The dataset reports total emissions in CO2 equivalents, broken down by greenhouse gas types (CO2, CH4, N2O, F-gases) and by economic sectors. 2024 data shows 649 million tonnes CO2-equivalent, representing a 48.2% reduction since 1990 and a 3.4% reduction from 2023. Includes emissions development trends, sectoral breakdowns, and progress toward national and European climate targets.

structured_data.name: Energiebedingte Emissionen von Klimagasen und Luftschadstoffen
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with embedded visualizations and downloadable PDF charts
structured_data.data_format: Web page with embedded charts, PDF diagrams
structured_data.description: Dataset from Umweltbundesamt (German Federal Environment Agency) documenting energy-related greenhouse gas and air pollutant emissions in Germany. Covers emissions from conversion of fossil fuels (coal, natural gas, mineral oil) into electricity and heat, as well as emissions from transport sector combustion engines and diffuse emissions. Data shows that energy-related emissions constituted approximately 85% of German greenhouse gas emissions in 2022, with the energy sector (public power and heat generation, refineries) being the primary source at 39%. Includes analysis of CO2 emissions from electricity generation, greenhouse gas composition (98% CO2, with CH4 and N2O), and trends since 1990 showing general decline with temporary disruptions in 2009 and 2020. Updated as of December 20, 2024.

structured_data.name: Umweltökonomische Gesamtrechnungen - Energieflüsse und Emissionen
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query through Destatis website
structured_data.description: German Federal Statistical Office (Destatis) environmental-economic accounts covering energy flows and emissions. This is a comprehensive statistical resource on environmental topics including greenhouse gas emissions data for Germany. The dataset is part of Destatis's broader environmental statistics offerings under the 'Umwelt, Umweltökonomische Gesamtrechnungen' (Environment, Environmental-Economic Accounts) section.

decision_log.summary: Reviewed 7 documents from German official sources. This is a highly promising batch with multiple authoritative government and environmental agency sources. Four documents are directly relevant to transportation sector emissions data for Germany, with strong indicators of containing structured data, tables, and downloadable datasets. Two additional documents provide broader GHGI context. One document appears to be primarily navigation/menu content with limited substantive data.
decision_log.reasoning: Identified five highly credible documents from Germany's primary statistical and environmental authorities (Umweltbundesamt, KBA, Destatis). The UBA documents explicitly reference structured data tools (TREMOD model, HBEFA handbook), downloadable tables in Excel format, and detailed emission figures for transportation. The KBA document contains specific vehicle fleet statistics with numerical data. These sources are ideal for detailed GHGI data extraction, particularly for the transportation sector. The documents show clear evidence of containing tables, datasets, and quantified emission metrics.

decision_log.summary: Excellent collection of authoritative German government sources for GHGI data. All six extracted datasets are from highly credible official sources (Destatis, KBA, UBA) covering transportation and energy sectors with national-level granularity. The data spans multiple GHGI categories and includes both activity data (vehicle fleet, fuel sales) and emissions data (CO2, CH4, N2O, F-gases) from 1990 onwards. Sources are current (updated through May 2025 for some datasets). The extraction captures key metadata accurately. Primary limitation is that some datasets require deeper exploration of sub-pages to access specific tables/files, but this is typical for government statistical portals.
decision_log.reasoning: While the sources are highly credible and clearly relevant, a deep_dive is warranted rather than immediate acceptance because: (1) The extraction describes portal/gateway pages rather than direct access to specific datasets - KBA and Destatis URLs appear to be navigation hubs requiring sub-page exploration; (2) Specific data tables on fuel sales by type, vehicle-kilometres by category, and electricity consumption for road transport are mentioned in descriptions but not confirmed as directly accessible from the provided URLs; (3) UBA's 'Emissionen des Verkehrs' mentions downloadable Excel files but these are not directly linked; (4) The search plan queries specifically target fuel sales, vehicle kilometres, and electricity consumption data - these need confirmation of availability and format from the actual data pages. A focused deep_dive will confirm data accessibility, identify specific file/table locations, and extract actual numerical data ranges to validate completeness for GHGI reporting requirements.

decision_log.refinement_details_processed: Conduct targeted deep_dive on three priority sources: (1) KBA Fahrzeugbestand - Navigate to vehicle fleet data tables and confirm availability of breakdown by fuel type (gasoline, diesel, LPG, electric, hybrid) and vehicle category (passenger cars, light commercial, heavy-duty); extract sample data for 2023-2024. (2) UBA Emissionen des Verkehrs - Locate and download Excel data files; extract CO2 emissions by vehicle type and fuel type for 2020-2023; confirm vehicle-kilometres data availability. (3) Destatis Güterverkehr - Explore freight transport statistics for activity data (tonne-kilometres, vehicle-kilometres) by transport mode and fuel type. Secondary: Verify UGR dataset for electricity consumption in road transport (e-vehicles). Expected outcome: Confirm specific data availability, file formats, and numerical ranges to proceed with data extraction for GHGI compilation.

decision_log.summary: Excellent collection of official German government sources for GHGI data. The extracted structured data includes primary sources from Destatis (Federal Statistical Office) and Umweltbundesamt (Federal Environment Agency), which are the authoritative bodies for German greenhouse gas inventory reporting. The data covers transportation sector activity data (vehicle fleet, freight transport) and comprehensive emissions data across multiple sectors. All sources are credible, national-level government agencies with established GHGI reporting responsibilities.
decision_log.reasoning: This dataset collection meets all ACCEPT criteria: (1) Official national GHGI activity data for Germany is confirmed available from government statistical offices; (2) Credible sources from Destatis and UBA, which are responsible for Germany's official GHGI reporting; (3) Key emission categories for transportation sector are covered (vehicle fleet, fuel types, emissions by vehicle category); (4) Strong indication that these websites contain desired data - the descriptions explicitly mention downloadable files, databases, and detailed breakdowns. The sources are not merely general references but specific GHGI data portals. National-level data is appropriate for GHGI purposes and is available from these authoritative sources. No credibility or relevance concerns exist. Further deep dives would be redundant given the authoritative nature of these sources and the comprehensive coverage demonstrated.
